revision.text:
'''Constituent country''' is a term sometimes used in contexts in which a [[country]] makes up a part of a larger political entity, such as a [[sovereign state]]. The term ''constituent country'' does not have any [[term of art|defined legal meaning]], and is used simply to refer to a ''country'' which is a constituent part of something else.

==In unitary states==
===Denmark===
{{Main|Danish Realm}}

The [[Danish Realm]] consists of three constituent parts, each part sometimes referred to as a country:
* [[Denmark]] proper
* The [[Faroe Islands]]<ref>The West Nordic Council. [http://www.vestnordisk.is/Apps/WebObjects/SW.woa/wa/dp?id=1295 website]. Retrieved 8 March 2011.</ref>
* [[Greenland]]<ref>[[Royal Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]. [http://www.ambottawa.um.dk/Publikationer/UM/English/FactsheetDenmark/Greenland/pdf/Greenland_2004.pdf Factsheet Denmark: Greenland].</ref>

However, this terminology is not consistent. The Faroes are also referred to as a "self-governing territory" or similar by (e.g.) the [[Prime Minister of the Faroe Islands]]<ref>Prime Minister of the Faroe Islands. "[http://www.tinganes.fo/Default.aspx?ID=2419 About the Faroe Islands]". Retrieved 8 March 2011</ref> and the [[Royal Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs]].<ref>Royal Danish Ministry of Foreign Affairs. [http://www.denmark.dk/NR/rdonlyres/9D235E97-31D2-4DE4-A03A-932195712BAA/0/023TheFaroes.pdf Factsheet Denmark – the Faroes].</ref> Similarly, the Danish Government also refers to Greenland as an "autonomous province"<ref>Danish Government.{{Dubious|date=September 2011}} "[http://www.denmark.dk/en/menu/About-Denmark/Denmark-In-Brief Denmark in Brief]".</ref> and neither of the laws forming Greenland's constitution refer to Greenland as a country.<ref>The "[http://uk.nanoq.gl/~/media/f74bab3359074b29aab8c1e12aa1ecfe.ashx Act on Greenland Self-Government 2008]" refers to Greenland as a "people" and the "[http://www.faqs.org/minorities/Appendices/The-Greenland-Home-Rule-Act-Act-No-577-of-29-November-1978-Extracts.html Greenland Home Rule Act 1978]" referred to Greenland as a "community".</ref>

===France===
{{Main|Overseas country of France}}
French regions (e.g., [[Pays d'Auge]], [[Pays de la Loire]], and [[Pays de Caux]]) often bear the appellation ''{{linktext|pays}}'' ("land"), which is sometimes also used in reference to other nations (e.g., ''[[Pays-Bas]]'' is the French name of the [[Netherlands]]).

In 2004, the French [[overseas collectivity]] of [[French Polynesia]] was legally designated as a ''pays d'outre-mer au sein de la République'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=LEGITEXT000005765456&dateTexte=vig |title=Loi organique n°2004-192 du 27 février 2004 |language={{fr icon}} |publisher=Legifrance.gouv.fr |date= |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref> translated as an "[[Overseas country of France|overseas country inside the Republic]]".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/country_profiles/3826525.stm Regions and territories: French Polynesia] BBC, 11 December 2010, retrieved 8 March 2011</ref> The [[Constitutional Council of France]] ruled that this was merely a change of appellation and did not represent a constitutional change in legal status.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/conseil-constitutionnel/francais/les-decisions/acces-par-date/decisions-depuis-1959/2004/2004-490-dc/decision-n-2004-490-dc-du-12-fevrier-2004.892.html |title=Décision n° 2004-490 DC du 12 février 2004 |publisher=Conseil-constitutionnel.fr |date= |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>

===Netherlands===
{{Main|Kingdom of the Netherlands}}
From 10 October 2010, the Kingdom of the Netherlands consists of four countries:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stabroeknews.com/2010/news/regional/10/09/netherlands-antilles-no-more/ |title=Netherlands Antilles no more - Stabroek News - Guyana |publisher=Stabroek News |date=2010-10-09 |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>
* [[Netherlands]] proper
* [[Aruba]]
* [[Curaçao]]
* [[Sint Maarten]]

Each is expressly designated as a ''land'' in Dutch law by the [[Charter for the Kingdom of the Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lexius.nl/statuut-voor-het-koninkrijk-der-nederlanden/artikel1 |title=Article 1 of the Charter for the Kingdom of the Netherlands |publisher=Lexius.nl |date= |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref> Unlike the German and Austrian ''Bundesländer'', ''landen'' is consistently translated as "countries" by the Dutch government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.minbzk.nl/subjects/aruba-and-the |title=Dutch Ministry of the Interior and Kingdom Relations -Aruba |publisher=English.minbzk.nl |date=2003-01-24 |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref><ref name= SMN>[http://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/5291-the-kingdom-of-the-netherlands-new-constitutional-structure.html St Martin News Network] 18 November 2010</ref><ref name= Newstatus>{{cite web|url=http://english.minbzk.nl/subjects/aruba-and-the/new-status-for-the/@122971/10-10-10-end-of-the |title=Dutch Ministry of the Interior and Kingdom Relations - New Status |publisher=English.minbzk.nl |date=2009-10-01 |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>

===New Zealand===
{{main|Realm of New Zealand}}
The [[Realm of New Zealand]] consists of three parts usually referred to as countries:

* [[New Zealand]] proper
* [[Cook Islands]]<ref>Cook Islands Government. "[http://www.cook-islands.gov.ck/cook-islands.php The Cook Islands Government Online]". Retrieved 8 March 2011.</ref><ref>Australian Government. "[http://www.ausaid.gov.au/country/country.cfm?CountryId=27 AusAid]". Retrieved 8 March 2008.</ref>
* [[Niue]]<ref>Australian Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade. "[http://www.dfat.gov.au/geo/niue/index.html Niue]". Retrieved 8 March 2011.</ref>

However, the Constitutions of the Cook Islands<ref>"[http://www.paclii.org/ck/legis/num_act/cotci327/ Constitution of the Cook Islands]".</ref> and of Niue<ref>"[http://www.paclii.org/nu/legis/consol_act/con231/ Constitution of Niue]".</ref> do not describe either as a country, nor do the New Zealand Acts which brought those constitutions into force.<ref>"[http://www.paclii.org/ck/legis/ck-nz_act/ca1986188/ New Zealand legislation - Cook Islands]".</ref><ref>"[http://www.legislation.govt.nz/act/public/1974/0042/latest/DLM412793.html New Zealand legislation - Niue]".</ref>

===United Kingdom===
[[File:United Kingdom labelled map7.png|thumb|180px|Constituent countries of the UK.]]
{{Main|Countries of the United Kingdom|History of the formation of the United Kingdom}}

The United Kingdom is generally considered to comprise four countries:<ref name="countries within a country">Number 10.gov.uk. "[http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page823.asp Countries within a Country]."{{Dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref><ref>[[Office for National Statistics]]. "[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/guide-method/geography/beginner-s-guide/glossary/glossary-c.html Glossary]".</ref><ref>Statistics.gov.uk. "[http://www.statistics.gov.uk/census2001/profiles/commentaries/ethnicity.asp 2001 British Census]".{{Dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref><ref>British Embassy in the United States of America. "[http://ukinusa.fco.gov.uk/en/aboutuk/visitinguk/countries-inthe-uk Countries in the UK]".{{Dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref>

* [[England]]
* [[Scotland]]
* [[Wales]]
* [[Northern Ireland]]

However, the kingdom itself is a ''[[unitary state|unitary]]'' one and not a [[personal union]]. The [[principality of Wales]] ceased to exist in [[Laws in Wales Acts 1535–1542|1542]], the kingdoms of [[Kingdom of England|England]] and [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scotland]] in [[Acts of Union 1707|1707]], and the [[kingdom of Ireland]] in [[Acts of Union 1800|1801]] (or 1953<ref name="Burke">The year [[Elizabeth II]] ceased to be styled ''Queen of Great Britain, Ireland, &c.'' and was instead styled ''Queen of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, &c.'' See: [[Titles of Elizabeth II#Europe|Titles of Elizabeth II]].</ref>). Further, the word ''country'' does not always appear in the acts of union which established the modern nation. The term can be particularly controversial when applied to Northern Ireland, which was created when [[Partition of Ireland|Ireland was partitioned]] in 1921.

Northern Ireland had a [[Parliament of Northern Ireland|devolved parliament]] from 1921–73 and an [[Northern Ireland Assembly|assembly]] from 1973–74, 1982–86, and 1999 to the present. After referenda in Wales and Scotland in 1997, new [[devolution in the United Kingdom|devolved governments]] were created in [[Scottish Parliament|Scotland]], [[National Assembly for Wales|Wales]] but not England, which remains directly under the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] in London.

At sporting events such as [[rugby union]], an alternate title, [[Home Nations]] is used, which in these contexts sometimes includes [[Ireland]] as a whole.

==In federal states==
===Soviet Union===
{{main|Republics of the Soviet Union}}
The [[Soviet Union]] was a Union of the free associate Soviet Socialist Republics, by constitution. In reality, the Union was represented as a single uniform state.

